### Description

Given the child component:

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  standalone: true,
  template: ``,
  inputs: ['classProp', 'declarationProp']
})
export class ChildComponent {
  classProp: string = '';
}

export declare interface ChildComponent {
  declarationProp: string;
}
```

And the root component:
```ts
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { ChildComponent } from './child.component';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [ChildComponent],
  template: `
    <app-child [classProp]="0" [declarationProp]="0" #child/>
    {{child.classProp.foo()}}
    {{child.declarationProp.foo()}}
  `
})
export class AppComponent { }
```

The template tries to set the inputs of `ChildComponent`, `classProp` and `declarationProp`, to a number value. The `classProp` failes, but the type of `declarationProp` is not recognized and no error is thrown (and there is no intellisense).

Using the reference to #child, both `child.classProp.foo()` and `child.declarationProp.foo()` failes as expected, and the type is recognized as string for both.

I would expect the template type checker to respect the declaration merging when setting input properties.



### Minimal Reproduction

https://github.com/kristilw/bug-angular-template-type-checker

When running `npm start` or `npm build` , would expect it to throw error when the wrong type on input property.

